Flu Shot Learning

Context

The DrivenData website launched a data competition on H1N1 and seasonal flu vaccination. The objective is to predict how likely individuals are to receive their flu vaccines based on data and information collected in a phone survey.

The data for this competition comes from the National 2009 H1N1 Flu Survey (NHFS). In their own words:

The National 2009 H1N1 Flu Survey (NHFS) was sponsored by the National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases (NCIRD) and conducted jointly by NCIRD and the National Center for Health Statistics (NCHS), Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The NHFS was a list-assisted random-digit-dialing telephone survey of households, designed to monitor influenza immunization coverage in the 2009-10 season. The target population for the NHFS was all persons 6 months or older living in the United States at the time of the interview. Data from the NHFS were used to produce timely estimates of vaccination coverage rates for both the monovalent pH1N1 and trivalent seasonal influenza vaccines.

According to Google based on U.S. Census Bureau data, the total population in the USA in 209 was approximately 306.8 million. With a training dataset including 26708 respondants (with respondant 0) it therefore represents approximately 0.0087% of the population. Given that the survey was as list-assisted random-digit-dialing telephone survey of households in the USA, it is reasonable to consider the sample representative of the whole population.

Data description

The description for the variables below are from the DrivenData website:

There are two target variables (multilabel problem) and both are binary variables(0 = No; 1 = Yes):

  • h1n1_vaccine - Whether respondent received H1N1 flu vaccine.
  • seasonal_vaccine - Whether respondent received seasonal flu vaccine.

There are 36 features in this dataset, hence a dataset with 36 columns. The first column respondent_id is a unique and random identifier. The remaining 35 features are described below. For all binary variables: 0 = No; 1 = Yes.

  • h1n1_concern - Level of concern about the H1N1 flu.
    • 0 = Not at all concerned; 1 = Not very concerned; 2 = Somewhat concerned; 3 = Very concerned.
  • h1n1_knowledge - Level of knowledge about H1N1 flu.
    • 0 = No knowledge; 1 = A little knowledge; 2 = A lot of knowledge.
  • behavioral_antiviral_meds - Has taken antiviral medications. (binary)
  • behavioral_avoidance - Has avoided close contact with others with flu-like symptoms. (binary)
  • behavioral_face_mask - Has bought a face mask. (binary)
  • behavioral_wash_hands - Has frequently washed hands or used hand sanitizer. (binary)
  • behavioral_large_gatherings - Has reduced time at large gatherings. (binary)
  • behavioral_outside_home - Has reduced contact with people outside of own household. (binary)
  • behavioral_touch_face - Has avoided touching eyes, nose, or mouth. (binary)
  • doctor_recc_h1n1 - H1N1 flu vaccine was recommended by doctor. (binary)
  • doctor_recc_seasonal - Seasonal flu vaccine was recommended by doctor. (binary)
  • chronic_med_condition - Has any of the following chronic medical conditions: asthma or an other lung condition, diabetes, a heart condition, a kidney condition, sickle cell anemia or other anemia, a neurological or neuromuscular condition, a liver condition, or a weakened immune system caused by a chronic illness or by medicines taken for a chronic illness. (binary)
  • child_under_6_months - Has regular close contact with a child under the age of six months. (binary)
  • health_worker - Is a healthcare worker. (binary)
  • health_insurance - Has health insurance. (binary)
  • opinion_h1n1_vacc_effective - Respondents opinion about H1N1 vaccine effectiveness.
    • 1 = Not at all effective; 2 = Not very effective; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat effective; 5 = Very effective.
  • opinion_h1n1_risk - Respondents opinion about risk of getting sick with H1N1 flu without vaccine.
    • 1 = Very Low; 2 = Somewhat low; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat high; 5 = Very high.
  • opinion_h1n1_sick_from_vacc - Respondents worry of getting sick from taking H1N1 vaccine.
    • 1 = Not at all worried; 2 = Not very worried; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat worried; 5 = Very worried.
  • opinion_seas_vacc_effective - Respondents opinion about seasonal flu vaccine effectiveness.
    • 1 = Not at all effective; 2 = Not very effective; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat effective; 5 = Very effective.
  • opinion_seas_risk - Respondents opinion about risk of getting sick with seasonal flu without vaccine.
    • 1 = Very Low; 2 = Somewhat low; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat high; 5 = Very high.
  • opinion_seas_sick_from_vacc - Respondents worry of getting sick from taking seasonal flu vaccine.
    • 1 = Not at all worried; 2 = Not very worried; 3 = Dont know; 4 = Somewhat worried; 5 = Very worried.
  • age_group - Age group of respondent.
  • education - Self-reported education level.
  • race - Race of respondent.
  • sex - Sex of respondent.
  • income_poverty - Household annual income of respondent with respect to 2008 Census poverty thresholds.
  • marital_status - Marital status of respondent.
  • rent_or_own - Housing situation of respondent.
  • employment_status - Employment status of respondent.
  • hhs_geo_region - Respondents residence using a 10-region geographic classification defined by the U.S. Dept. of Health and Human Services. Values are represented as short random character strings.
  • census_msa - Respondents residence within metropolitan statistical areas (MSA) as defined by the U.S. Census.
  • household_adults - Number of other adults in household, top-coded to 3.
  • household_children - Number of children in household, top-coded to 3.
  • employment_industry - Type of industry respondent is employed in. Values are represented as short random character strings.
  • employment_occupation - Type of occupation of respondent. Values are represented as short random character strings.

What if we consider both vaccines? How many participants got either no vaccination, H1N1 vaccine only, seasonal flu vaccine only, both vaccines?

none <- sum(train_all$h1n1_vaccine == 0 & train_all$seasonal_vaccine == 0)

seasonal <- sum(train_all$h1n1_vaccine == 0 & train_all$seasonal_vaccine == 1)
both <- sum(train_all$h1n1_vaccine == 1 & train_all$seasonal_vaccine == 1)

The respondant_id variable is common to both datasets (training and testing) and has no missing values. The two variables only found in the training dataset, the h1n1_vaccine and the seasonal_vaccine variables, also have no NAs. For the remaining of the variables, we see that trends in missing values seem to be the same in the training and the testing datasets. In both cases, the employment variables (industry and occupation) are missing for approximately 50% of respondants; the health_insurance variable is missing for approximately 46% of respondants; the income variable is missing for almost 17% of respondants; whether the H1N1 or the seasonal vaccines had been recommended by their doctors is missing for 8% of respondants; and whether the respondant owns or rents is missing for almost 8% of respondants. Finally, education, marital status and employment status are also missing for approximately 5% of respondants.

We will have to deal with NAs, but given that they are in both datasets may want to not use the variables with most missing values?

NEXT STEPS

(Try to create the above plots through a loop.)

The next step is to build a model that, based on survey answers, will predict the float probabilities (ranging between 0.0 and 1.0) of each participant to have taken the H1N1 and/or the seasonal flu shot(s), or in other words the probabilities that a person received each vaccine. As this is a multilabel problem, the submission file should include a probability for each vaccine.

What is a multilabel problem?

Based on the scikit learn website, multilabel classification assigns to each sample a set of target labels so predicting properties of a data-point that are not mutually exclusive. For example, a text might be about any of religion, politics, finance or education at the same time or none of these. On the opposite, multiclass classification means a classification task with more than two classes; e.g., classify a set of images of fruits which may be oranges, apples, or pears. Multiclass classification makes the assumption that each sample is assigned to one and only one label: a fruit can be either an apple or a pear but not both at the same time.

OK, so we have several binary and categorical variables to model probabilities of vaccination.

Given that we are trying to predict whether the participants took the flu, this can be predict with a logistic regression model. This was also the approach that Jay Qi, Senior Scientist at DrivenData took during his workshop at the goodtechfest.com but implemented in Python 3. This is the same as the benchmark code example on the DrivenData website for this competition. His pipeline included two pre-processing steps being (1) scaling all variables on the same scales and (2) NA imputation as logistic regresssion cannot deal with NAs. His first pass model included all numerical variables.

I will take a very similar approach here, but implemented in R, and with a selection of variables based on the plots.

Build models with recipes from Tidymodels

set.seed(1234)
data_split <- initial_split(train_all)
train_data <- training(data_split)
test_data <- testing(data_split)
recipe_simple <- function(dataset) {
  recipe(Churn ~ ., data = dataset) %>%
    step_string2factor(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
    prep(data = dataset)
}

Recipe for data preprocessing - do not put variables that are correlated into a logistic regression

pre_processing <- recipe(h1n1_vaccine ~ ., data = train_data) %>%
  step_corr(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal(), -all_outcomes()) %>%
  step_zv(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric()) %>% #centering and scaling 
  prep()
